## An APU (Application Processing Unit) is a type of computer processor developed mainly by Advanced Micro Devices (AMD). It combines a CPU and a GPU on the same chip.

### What an APU Does
An APU performs two main roles in one processor:
    CPU (Central Processing Unit) tasks
        Runs programs
        Handles operating system operations
        Performs general computing tasks
    GPU (Graphics Processing Unit) tasks
        Renders graphics
        Handles video playback
        Supports light gaming and graphical workloads
Because both are integrated into one chip, the system does not need a separate graphics card for basic graphics.



## A Real-Time Processing Unit (RPU) is a processor designed to handle tasks that must be completed immediately within strict timing constraints. It ensures that data is processed as soon as it arrives, often within microseconds or milliseconds.

### An RPU is responsible for deterministic processing, meaning the system guarantees that operations happen within a predictable time limit.

Typical responsibilities include:
    Processing sensor data instantly
    Controlling hardware devices
    Handling real-time communication signals
    Running control loops for machines

Why Real-Time Processing Is Important
In many systems, delays are unacceptable. If processing happens too late, the system may fail or behave incorrectly.

Examples:
    🚗 Autonomous vehicles must react immediately to obstacles.
    🏭 Industrial robots must adjust movements in real time.
    📡 Telecommunications systems must process signals instantly.